    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Antimicrobial Stewardship", content: "the clinician manages Antimicrobial Stewardship through advanced understanding of respiratory pathophysiology, ventilation-perfusion relationships, and airway dynamics. Assessment includes comprehensive respiratory history, systematic pulmonary examination (inspection of respiratory pattern, palpation for tactile fremitus, percussion for consolidation or hyperresonance, auscultation of breath sounds including crackles, wheezes, rhonchi, and diminished breath sounds), and interpretation of diagnostic studies (arterial blood gases with systematic acid-base analysis, pulmonary function tests including spirometry with bronchodilator response, chest imaging interpretation, and relevant biomarkers). The clinician applies evidence-based algorithms to differentiate obstructive from restrictive pathology, identifies acute versus chronic processes, and recognizes respiratory emergencies requiring immediate intervention. Pharmacotherapy selection is based on pathophysiological mechanism: bronchodilators for airway smooth muscle constriction (beta-2 agonists and anticholinergics), anti-inflammatory agents for airway inflammation (inhaled corticosteroids, leukotriene modifiers), antimicrobials for infectious processes (guided by culture data, local resistance patterns, and antimicrobial stewardship principles), and oxygen therapy titrated to appropriate SpO2 targets. The clinician coordinates multidisciplinary respiratory care, manages exacerbation action plans, and determines criteria for escalation of care." },
